abstract.text: The quality of the remote audio stream in the reported interval. The quality is determined by the Agora real-time audio MOS (Mean Opinion Score) measurement method. The return value range is [0, 500]. Dividing the return value by 100 gets the MOS score, which ranges from 0 to 5. The higher the score, the better the audio quality.The subjective perception of audio quality corresponding to the Agora real-time audio MOS scores is as follows:MOS scorePerception of audio qualityGreater than 4Excellent. The audio sounds clear and smooth.From 3.5 to 4Good. The audio has some perceptible impairment but still sounds clear.From 3 to 3.5Fair. The audio freezes occasionally and requires attentive listening.From 2.5 to 3Poor. The audio sounds choppy and requires considerable effort to understand.From 2 to 2.5Bad. The audio has occasional noise. Consecutive audio dropouts occur, resulting in some information loss. The users can communicate only with difficulty.Less than 2Very bad. The audio has persistent noise. Consecutive audio dropouts are frequent, resulting in severe information loss. Communication is nearly impossible.
Audio statistics of the remote user.

The quality of the remote audio stream in the reported interval. The quality is determined by the Agora real-time audio MOS (Mean Opinion Score) measurement method. The return value range is [0, 500]. Dividing the return value by 100 gets the MOS score, which ranges from 0 to 5. The higher the score, the better the audio quality.The subjective perception of audio quality corresponding to the Agora real-time audio MOS scores is as follows:MOS scorePerception of audio qualityGreater than 4Excellent. The audio freezes occasionally and requires attentive listening.From 2.5 to 3Poor. The audio sounds choppy and requires considerable effort to understand.From 2 to 2.5Bad. The audio has persistent noise. Consecutive audio dropouts are frequent, resulting in severe information loss. Communication is nearly impossible.
